  <figure xml:id="fig_ODV_Temp_vs_Lat">
    <caption>The average temperature of the deep oceans, here in the Atlantic. Below the thin surface layer <nbsp/>600 meters (2000 feet) deep, the oceans are monotonously cold, averaging between \SIrange{1}{3}{\celsius} (<m>34-37 \deg</m>F). When combined with the monotonous salinity variations (<xref ref="fig_salinity_sect">Figure</xref>, and the fact that sea water density is largely controlled by salinity and density, we conclude that density variations in the deep ocean must be subtle. Tiny difference in temperature and salinity can have profound effects on density, and hence circulation, of seawater.</caption>
